    <h1 id="great-blue-heron-identification-size-plumage-and-field-marks">Great Blue Heron Identification: Size, Plumage, and Field Marks</h1>
<p>The Great Blue Heron is one of the easiest large birds to identify in North America — as the Cornell Lab of Ornithology puts it, there is "no other similar species in range."<sup id="fnref:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup> It is the largest of the North American herons, built on long legs, a sinuous neck, and a thick, daggerlike bill, with head, chest, and wing plumes that give adults a shaggy appearance.<sup id="fnref:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup> In flight it curls its neck into a tight "S" shape, its broad, rounded wings beat slowly, and its legs trail well beyond the tail.<sup id="fnref2:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="measurements">Measurements</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Measurement</th>
<th>Range (both sexes)</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Length</td>
<td>38.2–53.9 in (97–137 cm)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Weight</td>
<td>74.1–88.2 oz (2,100–2,500 g)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Wingspan</td>
<td>65.8–79.1 in (167–201 cm)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Standing height</td>
<td>Up to ~4–4.5 ft (115–138 cm)<sup id="fnref2:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Bill</td>
<td>Long, straight, ~5–6 in<sup id="fnref:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Figures from the Cornell Lab's All About Birds guide.<sup id="fnref3:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup> Regional studies add nuance: in British Columbia, adult males averaged 2.48 kg and females 2.11 kg; Nova Scotia/New England adults of both sexes averaged 2.23 kg; Oregon birds averaged 2.09 kg. The all-white "great white heron" population of south Florida is the heaviest, with males averaging 3.02 kg.<sup id="fnref:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup> Despite the imposing frame, hollow bones keep the bird light enough to fly high and efficiently.<sup id="fnref:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="plumage-and-color-pattern">Plumage and color pattern</h2>
<p>Adults are predominantly blue-gray above, with a mostly white head crossed by a wide black stripe that runs from above the eye to the back of the head, ending in short black plumes. The foreneck is white streaked with black; the shoulders show a black-and-chestnut pattern; and the bill is yellow to yellow-orange (dark above, yellow below).<sup id="fnref2:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup> During the breeding season the colors intensify — the bill and lores brighten, and adults grow long, showy occipital plumes and shaggy neck and chest plumes used in courtship displays.<sup id="fnref:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup> Males and females look nearly identical, though males average larger with slightly longer ornamental plumes.<sup id="fnref:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="telling-age-and-sex">Telling age and sex</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Juveniles</strong> are duller and more uniformly gray than adults, with a solid dark crown (no white face framed by black), streaked necks, and no long head plumes.<sup id="fnref:9"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:9">9</a></sup><sup id="fnref:10"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:10">10</a></sup></li>
<li>Young birds acquire white streaking on the crown by their second fall and approach full adult plumage around their third year; they do not breed until at least two years old.<sup id="fnref2:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup><sup id="fnref:11"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:11">11</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Male vs. female</strong> is best judged by size when a pair stands together: females average noticeably smaller with smaller bills; plumage differences are minimal.<sup id="fnref3:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="flight-silhouette-the-giveaway">Flight silhouette — the giveaway</h2>
<p>Few sights are as diagnostic: broad, rounded wings with a two-toned look (paler leading edge, darker flight feathers), deep slow wingbeats, neck pulled back into a compact "S" with the head resting above the shoulders, and long legs streaming behind the tail.<sup id="fnref4:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup><sup id="fnref2:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup> The tucked neck instantly separates herons from cranes, which fly with necks outstretched.<sup id="fnref:12"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:12">12</a></sup> Cruising speed is roughly 20–30 mph, and GPS-tracked birds in Maine averaged about 24 mph in everyday flight.<sup id="fnref3:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup><sup id="fnref:13"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:13">13</a></sup></p>
<p><img alt="Size comparison of Great Blue Heron with Great Egret, Sandhill Crane, and Little Blue Heron" src="images/size-comparison.png" /></p>
